culled from ever-frolic smiles , That live in Beauty's dimpled cheek , Such sweetness as the heart beguiles , And turns the mighty strong to weak : To these ambrosial dew she joined , And over the flame of warm desire , Fanned by soft sighs , Love's gentlest wind , Dissolved , and made the charm entire

Where diffused on Venus' breast , First he felt ecstatic bliss , First her balmy lips he pressed , And devoured the new-made Kiss : But , OH my Muse , thy tattling tongue restrain , Her sacred rites what mortal dares
the blabbing swain To doubts , desires
deigned this Cyprian charm to pour With lavish bounty over the child : Since wherever the Siren moves along , In pleasing wonder chained is every tongue
